---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
---
<Layout title="Matt Sanford — CHEK-certified coaching for the long game" screenLabel="01 Home" active="home">
  <!-- HERO -->
  <section class="hero">
    <div
      class="hero-bg"
      id="heroBg"
      style="background-image: url('https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1464822759023-fed622ff2c3b?w=2200&q=80&auto=format&fit=crop')"
    ></div>
    <div class="hero-meta">
      <span>North Shore, Massachusetts</span>
      <b>43.6° N · 70.6° W</b>
      <span>Cape Cod &middot; The Whites</span>
    </div>
    <div class="container hero-inner">
      <h1 id="heroTitle">Train for the <em>rest</em> of your life.</h1>
      <p class="hero-sub">
        CHEK-certified coaching for adults who want to feel sharp at 50,
        capable at 70, and on the trail well past either. Built on holistic
        assessment, modern strength science, and the lived experience of a Type
        1 athlete.
      </p>
      <div class="hero-cta-row">
        <a href="/contact" class="btn btn-primary">
          Book a movement assessment <span class="arrow">→</span>
        </a>
        <a href="/coaching" class="btn btn-ghost">How I coach</a>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="scrolldown">Scroll</div>
  </section>

  <!-- CREDS BAR -->
  <section class="tight">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="creds">
        <span><b style="color:var(--forest-deep);font-weight:500">CHEK</b> Institute Certified</span>
        <span class="dot"></span>
        <span>ACSM &middot; Resistance Training Position Stand 2026</span>
        <span class="dot"></span>
        <span>Functional Movement Screen</span>
        <span class="dot"></span>
        <span>Type 1 Diabetic since 2009</span>
        <span class="dot"></span>
        <span>NE 4,000-footers · 67/67</span>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- PILLARS -->
  <section>
    <div class="container">
      <div class="section-head">
        <span class="eyebrow">What I Coach</span>
        <h2>Three things, in this order, for the rest of your life.</h2>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="wide">
      <div class="pillars">
        <article class="pillar">
          <span class="num">i.</span>
          <h3>Move Well</h3>
          <p>
            Posture, breath, and the seven primal patterns — bend, squat,
            lunge, push, pull, twist, gait. Every program starts with an
            assessment, not a stock template. We fix what the body prioritizes
            first.
          </p>
          <a href="/coaching" class="read">The Assessment →</a>
        </article>
        <article class="pillar">
          <span class="num">ii.</span>
          <h3>Build Strength</h3>
          <p>
            Heavy enough loads, full range, two to three sets, two days a week
            minimum. The 2026 ACSM position stand synthesized 137 reviews to
            say what coaches have known: do less, do it well, do it for years.
          </p>
          <a href="/coaching" class="read">The Method →</a>
        </article>
        <article class="pillar">
          <span class="num">iii.</span>
          <h3>Recover Like It Matters</h3>
          <p>
            Sleep is the program. Breath is the gear shift. Quiet is the
            multiplier. The CHEK <em>Dr. Quiet</em> framing meets the modern
            recovery literature — because no amount of training fixes the night
            you didn't sleep.
          </p>
          <a href="/coaching" class="read">The Multiplier →</a>
        </article>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ABOUT TEASER -->
  <section style="background: var(--paper-warm);">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="split reverse">
        <div class="split-text">
          <span class="eyebrow">The Coach</span>
          <h2 style="margin-top: 18px;">A math teacher, a mountain, a glucose monitor.</h2>
          <p style="margin-top: 24px; color: var(--granite); font-size: 18px; line-height: 1.65;">
            Matt was teaching geometry when the diagnosis came. Type 1 Diabetes
            doesn't let you coast — it makes the body legible in a way most
            people never get to see. That literacy is what turned a math
            teacher into a CHEK-certified coach who reads bodies the way he
            used to read proofs.
          </p>
          <p style="color: var(--granite); font-size: 18px; line-height: 1.65;">
            He coaches now out of a strength gym on the North Shore. The
            classroom moved outside.
          </p>
          <a href="/about" class="btn btn-ghost" style="margin-top: 16px;">
            Read the story <span class="arrow">→</span>
          </a>
        </div>
        <div
          class="split-image"
          style="background-image: url('https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1551632811-561732d1e306?w=1400&q=80&auto=format&fit=crop')"
        >
          <div class="caption">Mt. Madison · Northern Presidentials</div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- METHODOLOGY TEASER -->
  <section>
    <div class="container">
      <div class="section-head">
        <span class="eyebrow">Methodology</span>
        <h2>Holistic doesn't mean unscientific.</h2>
      </div>
      <div class="split">
        <div class="split-text">
          <p class="kicker" style="margin-bottom: 28px;">
            The CHEK Institute has spent thirty years building a system that
            treats the body the way the body actually works — as one piece.
          </p>
          <p style="color: var(--granite); font-size: 17px;">
            The <strong style="color:var(--forest-deep);font-weight:500">4 Doctors</strong>
            — Movement, Quiet, Happiness, Diet — name the four inputs that
            produce a healthy human. The
            <strong style="color:var(--forest-deep);font-weight:500">CHEK Totem Pole</strong>
            ranks the order in which the brain prioritizes survival systems,
            which is why a CHEK assessment goes well beyond a movement screen.
            The <strong style="color:var(--forest-deep);font-weight:500">7 Primal Patterns</strong>
            are the universal vocabulary of human movement — pick up a
            kettlebell, step off a granite ledge, and you'll find them all.
          </p>
          <p style="color: var(--granite); font-size: 17px;">
            Pair that system with the 2025 ACSM Guidelines, the 2026
            Resistance Training Position Stand, and the Functional Movement
            Screen, and you have a coaching practice that's both 30 years old
            and three months old.
          </p>
          <a href="/coaching" class="btn btn-ghost" style="margin-top: 12px;">
            The full methodology <span class="arrow">→</span>
          </a>
        </div>
        <div>
          <blockquote class="pullquote">
            A CHEK practitioner doesn't start a client with squats. We start
            with what the brain prioritizes first.
          </blockquote>
          <p class="fineprint" style="margin-top: 18px; color: var(--granite-soft);">
            — Adapted from Paul Chek's Totem Pole, c. 1994
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- T1D BAND -->
  <section style="background: var(--forest-deep); color: var(--dune-soft); margin-top: 40px;">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="split">
        <div
          class="split-image"
          style="background-image: url('https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1486218119243-13883505764c?w=1400&q=80&auto=format&fit=crop'); aspect-ratio: 5/4;"
        >
          <div class="caption">Pemigewasset Wilderness · September</div>
        </div>
        <div class="split-text">
          <span class="eyebrow" style="color: color-mix(in srgb, var(--dune) 70%, transparent);">
            The Differentiator
          </span>
          <h2 style="color: var(--paper); margin-top: 18px;">
            A real-time graph of the metabolism, on the arm of the coach.
          </h2>
          <p style="color: color-mix(in srgb, var(--dune) 90%, transparent); font-size: 18px; line-height: 1.65; margin-top: 22px;">
            Most CHEK practitioners can talk holistic health. Most strength
            coaches can talk programming. Very few are also their own most
            demanding case study — with a continuous glucose monitor reporting
            back every five minutes from the summit of Mount Washington.
          </p>
          <p style="color: color-mix(in srgb, var(--dune) 90%, transparent); font-size: 18px; line-height: 1.65;">
            If you're an active adult living with Type 1, that experience is
            the whole point.
          </p>
          <a href="/about" class="btn" style="background: var(--paper); color: var(--forest-deep); margin-top: 8px;">
            Living strong with Type 1 <span class="arrow">→</span>
          </a>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- TESTIMONIAL -->
  <section>
    <div class="container" style="display:grid;grid-template-columns: 220px 1fr; gap: 48px;">
      <span class="eyebrow" style="border-top: 1px solid var(--rule); padding-top: 14px;">
        In Their Words
      </span>
      <div>
        <blockquote class="pullquote" style="font-size: clamp(28px, 3.4vw, 46px); max-width: 28ch;">
          Matt is the first trainer who explained <em>why</em> before he
          explained what. Six months in, my back is quiet, my squats are
          heavier, and I climbed Lafayette without my knees complaining once.
        </blockquote>
        <p class="fineprint" style="margin-top: 22px; color: var(--granite); font-size: 14px; letter-spacing: 0.06em;">
          — D.K., 54 — Beverly, MA &nbsp;·&nbsp; client since 2024
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- FIELD NOTES PREVIEW -->
  <section>
    <div class="container">
      <div class="section-head">
        <span class="eyebrow">Field Notes</span>
        <h2>Slow writing about strength, sleep, and the long game.</h2>
      </div>
      <div class="posts">
        <a href="/notes" class="post">
          <div class="meta"><span>Methodology</span><span>· 6 min</span></div>
          <h3>What a CHEK assessment actually looks like</h3>
          <p>
            The intake takes ninety minutes. We start with breathing and end
            with the squat. Here's why that order matters more than most
            clients expect.
          </p>
        </a>
        <a href="/notes" class="post">
          <div class="meta"><span>Type 1</span><span>· 8 min</span></div>
          <h3>The two-day rule for T1D and exercise</h3>
          <p>
            A single bout of training writes glucose dynamics into the next 24
            to 48 hours. What that means for programming, dosing, and how to
            think about a hard hike on a Saturday.
          </p>
        </a>
        <a href="/notes" class="post">
          <div class="meta"><span>Hiking</span><span>· 11 min</span></div>
          <h3>How I trained for the Pemi Loop</h3>
          <p>
            A twelve-week block built around eccentric loading, Zone 2, and
            the unglamorous work of teaching ankles to listen to talus.
          </p>
        </a>
      </div>
      <div style="margin-top: 48px;">
        <a href="/notes" class="btn btn-ghost">All field notes <span class="arrow">→</span></a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- CTA BAND -->
  <section style="background: var(--dune); padding: 100px 0;">
    <div class="container" style="text-align: center;">
      <span class="eyebrow">Start Here</span>
      <h2 style="margin-top: 16px; max-width: 22ch; margin-left:auto; margin-right:auto;">
        Every program starts with a movement assessment. No two programs are
        the same.
      </h2>
      <p style="max-width: 56ch; margin: 24px auto 32px; color: var(--granite); font-size: 18px;">
        Ninety minutes. We look at how you stand, how you breathe, how you
        move through the seven patterns. You leave with a clear picture of
        what's working, what isn't, and what to do next — whether or not you
        decide to keep working with me.
      </p>
      <a href="/contact" class="btn btn-primary">
        Book your assessment <span class="arrow">→</span>
      </a>
    </div>
  </section>
</Layout>
